        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Like Anthony Lewis (column, Sept. 23), I am pleased with the House of Representatives bill softening the 1996 Immigration Act's retroactive provisions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Like Anthony Lewis (column, Sept. 23), I am pleased with the House of Representatives bill softening the 1996 Immigration Act's retroactive provisions.</p>
        <p>However, this bill fails to rectify the act's harsh treatment of immigrants sentenced to probation or minor prison terms. It will provide no relief, for example, for two immigrants you recently profiled (''Condemned Again for Old Crimes,'' news article, Aug. 30), Garibaldy Mejia and Alejandro Bontia. Under the bill, Mr. Mejia will remain in mandatory detention until the Immigration and Naturalization Service hears his case, and Mr. Bontia must be deported. Neither man has ever spent a day in prison.</p>
        <p>The House is right to try to amend the 1996 act. But it should do so in a systemic fashion that truly eliminates the act's retroactive provisions.</p>
        <p>LAURIE KOZUBA  Director, Citizens and Immigrants  for Equal Justice  Mesquite, Tex., Sept. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
